<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by Dr John Ball (DWB 05)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Dr John Ball</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> (DWB 05)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The debate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on different</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> powers over taxation at a sub-state level has moved forward not least because of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">taxation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">changes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">other </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">devolved regimes in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Europe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">together with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">suggestion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of greater taxation powers both for Scotland and Northern Ireland. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t the state level, evidence from the Republic of Ireland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and central European states ha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">further</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">emphasised the central role of different taxation levels in economic welfare.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">My view is that of an economist concerned at the state of the Welsh economy and the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">way in which</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> taxation powers and adjustments can be a useful and innovative tool of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">economic </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">development. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This submission therefore is not necessarily concerned with the amount of revenue </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">which</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> might accrue to the Assembly (important though that clearly is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> some suggestions </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on revenue </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are made below in section 4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">) but with the usefulness and appropriateness of using (limited) taxation powers as an instrument of economic development.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Preamble:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The principle of different rates of taxation within the UK is already established. Different rates are applied to VAT; individuals pay different rates of personal taxation, council taxes vary by definition upon geography. Both the Scottish Parliament and the Northern Ireland Assembly have powers to vary income tax and the power to vary corporation tax for the latter ha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> already been suggested. British dependant territories have different taxation rates, not least in rates of corporation tax. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Welsh economy has many structural disadvantages that are beyond the powers suggested by the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">draft </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">bill; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in reality </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">many of the powers to address these structural disadvantages are already devolved.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> However, the continued decline of the Welsh economy requires the development and use of a variety of appropriate instruments, not least that of taxation, a method that has been successfully used in many economies that have faced similar problems to the Welsh economy.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Reversing the decline</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of the Welsh economy and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">introducing growth has to be the over-riding priority of any government initiative whether by the Welsh or UK governments. It is within this context that this memorandum is presented.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is of co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">urse accepted that some of the ideas that follow may well be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">seen to be outside the remit of the current suggested legislation. Th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ere</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> argument however for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">presenting them at</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> this highly appropriate moment, especially since the draft bill Section 116B, (1) refers to powers to “…amend so as to specify as a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> additional devolved tax, a tax of any description…” and</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(2) “…</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">make any other modifications of the provisions relating to devolved taxes…”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The memorandum is presented in four sections –</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The relevance and usefulness of income tax as an instrument of economic development</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A discussion on the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">importance of stamp duty as an instrument of economic development</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">commentary on business taxation and economic development</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">iscussion on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">alternative taxation instruments and their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">potential </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">role in generating revenue</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Income Tax</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Fundamentally a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> lack of demand in the economy </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lies behind the problems of limited economic </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">–</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">social - welfare a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d can be addressed, certainly in part, by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">changes in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">personal t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">axation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that lead to greater spending power</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The ability to adjust</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> lower</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> income tax could be is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">an important and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">well-tried</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> means of injecting purchasing power into the economy to drive demand. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Whilst</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> further analysis involving different rates</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">overall spending power</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and diminishing returns</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is needed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">an elementary estimate of the amount that might be generated by lowering tax can be made. If</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 1% of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the amount of income tax raised </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">annually </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in Wales at £4.89bn (draft bill) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">was returned, this would have the potential spending power of £5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">0</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">million.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Although explicitly excluded from the draft bill, a further and indeed simpler way of using taxation to increase demand is to increase the personal taxation allowance.  Separate figures are unfortunately not available; however this is worthy of further research</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, especially with the low level of earnings in Wales</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">here is the risk that in the present general economic environment any individual increase in income would be saved or used to reduce debt. </span></li></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A further issue is l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eakages</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> from the Welsh economy, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a major</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">weakness</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of any injection of spending power</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">St</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">amp Duty</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> Land Tax</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> amount of finance accruing from this tax is relati</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">vely small. However, the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">impact on the economy of changes to this tax is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> substantial. Stamp duty can dampen (as it currently does) housing demand or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">drive it. The construction industry,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to which reference is made in the evidence base section of the draft bill, is in favour of a change. The construction industry,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> not least housing, is a major economic driver not</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ably</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> because of the wide range of different products and skills needed.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However, s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tamp duty is invariably seen as relevant only to the market for new ho</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">u</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n reality there is a substantial multiplier effect from the market in existing housing; purchasers often undertake improvements and alterations to the newl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> acquired (existing) property</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that involve purchases and services not necessarily connected with construction</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> such as household furnishings</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Corp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">oration Tax</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The success of low corporate tax economies – notably the Republic of Ireland - has highlighted the use of taxation as an important tool in economic development since it can be manipulated to encourage economic growth.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Whilst a move to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lower the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> tax would be welcome, t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he majo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">weakness</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the use of corporation tax </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s the assumption that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">its</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> us</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> attrac</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ts or</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> develop</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">successful limited li</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">abi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lity businesses (since on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ly they pay co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rporation tax). </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e maj</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ority of businesses in Wales tr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e outside the protection of limited li</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-s