ont-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> funds might be repaid.</span></li></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">An </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">increase</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in income tax would be an important sour</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ce of finance for the Assembly although this would </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">militate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> against its usefulness in economic development.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ales tax is an accepted way of raising taxation. An estimate can be based on the annual total VAT paid in Wales which is approximately £4bn; a 1% addition would raise some £40million</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> annually</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. This form of taxation is “painless” since purchasers would be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">les</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s aware </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">than</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> they </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">might  be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of differences in personal taxation.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Local tourist taxes are common in economies dependant on the industry. The latest figures show that total overnight stays in Wales generated £3bn; a 2% tax would raise £6million annually.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Other forms of tourist tax might </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">also </span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">be considered</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">January 2014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>